    <DNDTextStage id="5">
      <internalName>#1</internalName>
      <externalName>Graphs by Hamiltonian Cycle Count</externalName>
      <taskDescription>&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Order these graph types from 0 to most Hamiltonian cycles.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;input style=&quot;width: 100%; height: 200px;&quot; disabled=&quot;disabled&quot; name=&quot;draggable-pool&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; value=&quot;draggable_pool_1&quot;&gt;&lt;input style=&quot;width: 100%; height: 300px;&quot; disabled=&quot;disabled&quot; name=&quot;drop-area&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; value=&quot;drop_area_1&quot;&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</taskDescription>
      <feedbackRules id="6">
        <FeedbackRule id="7">
          <name>Feedback </name>
          <orderIndex>3</orderIndex>
          <validationExpression id="8">
            <code>ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(3, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;C&apos;), 0, 1) == 1</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </validationExpression>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Complete graph $K_5$ (C) should be last as it has the most Hamiltonian cycles (12 cycles). The cycle graph $C_6$ (B) has fewer (exactly 2 cycles).&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A (or D) $\to$ D (or A) $\to$ B $\to$ C&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
          <points>0</points>
          <terminal>true</terminal>
          <fieldsToBeMarked id="9"/>
        </FeedbackRule>
        <FeedbackRule id="10">
          <name>Feedback </name>
          <orderIndex>2</orderIndex>
          <validationExpression id="11">
            <code>ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(0, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;B&apos;), 1, ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(0, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;C&apos;), 1, ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(1, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;B&apos;), 1, ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(1, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;C&apos;), 1, 0)))) == 1</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </validationExpression>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Neither B (cycle graph $C_6$) nor C (complete graph $K_5$) should be in the first two positions. Both star graphs and path graphs have zero Hamiltonian cycles, so A and D belong at the start.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A (or D) $\to$ D (or A) $\to$ B $\to$ C&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
          <points>0</points>
          <terminal>true</terminal>
          <fieldsToBeMarked id="12"/>
        </FeedbackRule>
        <FeedbackRule id="13">
          <name>Feedback </name>
          <orderIndex>5</orderIndex>
          <validationExpression id="14">
            <code>evaluateInR(&quot;
  input &lt;- [input=drop_area_1]
  (input[[3]] %in% c(&apos;A&apos;,&apos;D&apos;)) || (input[[4]] %in% c(&apos;A&apos;,&apos;D&apos;))
&quot;)</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </validationExpression>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Both A (star graph with 5 leaves) and D (path graph with 6 vertices) have zero Hamiltonian cycles and should be in the first two positions. Star graphs lack the necessary connections, and path graphs cannot close into cycles.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A (or D) $\to$ D (or A) $\to$ B $\to$ C&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
          <points>0</points>
          <terminal>true</terminal>
          <fieldsToBeMarked id="15"/>
        </FeedbackRule>
        <FeedbackRule id="16">
          <name>Feedback </name>
          <orderIndex>4</orderIndex>
          <validationExpression id="17">
            <code>evaluateInR(&quot;
  input &lt;- [input=drop_area_1]
  first_two &lt;- sort(c(input[[1]], input[[2]]))
  correct_first_two &lt;- c(&apos;A&apos;, &apos;D&apos;)
  identical(first_two, correct_first_two) &amp;&amp; input[[4]] == &apos;C&apos; &amp;&amp; input[[3]] != &apos;B&apos;
&quot;)</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </validationExpression>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. You correctly identified that A and D have zero cycles and C has the most, but the third position should be B (cycle graph $C_6$), which has exactly 2 Hamiltonian cycles.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A (or D) $\to$ D (or A) $\to$ B $\to$ C&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
          <points>0</points>
          <terminal>true</terminal>
          <fieldsToBeMarked id="18"/>
        </FeedbackRule>
        <FeedbackRule id="19">
          <name>Feedback </name>
          <orderIndex>1</orderIndex>
          <validationExpression id="20">
            <code>evaluateInR(&quot;any(sapply([var=all_correct_sequences], identical, y = [input=drop_area_1]))&quot;)</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </validationExpression>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Correct. Both star graphs and path graphs have zero Hamiltonian cycles (A and D can be in either order). The cycle graph $C_6$ has exactly 2 Hamiltonian cycles. The complete graph $K_5$ has the most with 12 Hamiltonian cycles.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A (or D) $\to$ D (or A) $\to$ B $\to$ C&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
          <points>100</points>
          <terminal>true</terminal>
          <fieldsToBeMarked id="21"/>
        </FeedbackRule>
        <FeedbackRule id="22">
          <name>Feedback </name>
          <orderIndex>0</orderIndex>
          <validationExpression id="23">
            <code>sizeOfList([input=drop_area_1]) &lt; 4</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </validationExpression>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incomplete. You must arrange all 4 graph types in the drop area.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
          <points>0</points>
          <terminal>true</terminal>
          <fieldsToBeMarked id="24"/>
        </FeedbackRule>
      </feedbackRules>
