        <targetStage class="DNDTextStage" id="28">
          <internalName>#2</internalName>
          <externalName>Hamiltonian Likelihood Ordering</externalName>
          <taskDescription>&lt;div&gt;Order these graphs from most likely to least likely to have a Hamiltonian cycle based on their structural properties.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;input style=&quot;width: 100%; height: 200px;&quot; disabled=&quot;disabled&quot; name=&quot;draggable-pool&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; value=&quot;draggable_pool_1&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;input style=&quot;width: 100%; height: 300px;&quot; disabled=&quot;disabled&quot; name=&quot;drop-area&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; value=&quot;drop_area_1&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</taskDescription>
          <feedbackRules id="29">
            <FeedbackRule id="30">
              <name>Feedback </name>
              <orderIndex>0</orderIndex>
              <validationExpression id="31">
                <code>sizeOfList([input=drop_area_1]) &lt; 4</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </validationExpression>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incomplete. You must arrange all 4 graph types in the drop area.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
              <points>0</points>
              <terminal>true</terminal>
              <fieldsToBeMarked id="32"/>
            </FeedbackRule>
            <FeedbackRule id="33">
              <name>Feedback </name>
              <orderIndex>2</orderIndex>
              <validationExpression id="34">
                <code>ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(0, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;A&apos;), 0, 1) == 1</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </validationExpression>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Your first position is wrong. Complete graph $K_{10}$ (A) should be first as it has the highest likelihood of having a Hamiltonian cycle. Every complete graph $K_n$ for $n \geq 3$ is guaranteed to have Hamiltonian cycles.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A $\to$ C $\to$ D $\to$ B&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
              <points>0</points>
              <terminal>true</terminal>
              <fieldsToBeMarked id="35"/>
            </FeedbackRule>
            <FeedbackRule id="36">
              <name>Feedback </name>
              <orderIndex>1</orderIndex>
              <validationExpression id="37">
                <code>equalList([input=drop_area_1], [var=correctSequence])</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </validationExpression>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Correct. Complete graph $K_{10}$ (A) is guaranteed to have Hamiltonian cycles by Dirac&apos;s theorem. The graph with minimum degree 5 (C) also satisfies Dirac&apos;s theorem ($\delta \geq n/2$). The sparse random graph (D) may or may not have a Hamiltonian cycle. Trees (B) can never have Hamiltonian cycles as they contain no cycles at all.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A $\to$ C $\to$ D $\to$ B&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
              <points>100</points>
              <terminal>true</terminal>
              <fieldsToBeMarked id="38"/>
            </FeedbackRule>
            <FeedbackRule id="39">
              <name>Feedback </name>
              <orderIndex>4</orderIndex>
              <validationExpression id="40">
                <code>ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(0, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;A&apos;), ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(1, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;C&apos;), ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(2, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;D&apos;), 0, 1), 0), 0) == 1</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </validationExpression>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Positions A and C are correct, but your third position is wrong. The random connected graph with 10 vertices and 12 edges (D) should be third. With only 12 edges, the average degree is $12/10 = 1.2$, which provides no theoretical guarantee but leaves open the possibility of a Hamiltonian cycle.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A $\to$ C $\to$ D $\to$ B&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
              <points>0</points>
              <terminal>true</terminal>
              <fieldsToBeMarked id="41"/>
            </FeedbackRule>
            <FeedbackRule id="42">
              <name>Feedback </name>
              <orderIndex>3</orderIndex>
              <validationExpression id="43">
                <code>ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(0, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;A&apos;), ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(1, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;C&apos;), 0, 1), 0) == 1</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </validationExpression>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Position A is correct, but your second position is wrong. After the complete graph (A), the graph with minimum degree 5 (C) should come next. By Dirac&apos;s theorem, a graph with $n$ vertices and minimum degree $\delta \geq n/2$ is guaranteed to have a Hamiltonian cycle. Since $\delta = 5$ and $n/2 = 5$, option C satisfies this condition.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A $\to$ C $\to$ D $\to$ B&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
              <points>0</points>
              <terminal>true</terminal>
              <fieldsToBeMarked id="44"/>
            </FeedbackRule>
            <FeedbackRule id="45">
              <name>Feedback </name>
              <orderIndex>5</orderIndex>
              <validationExpression id="46">
                <code>ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(0, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;A&apos;), ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(1, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;C&apos;), ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(2, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;D&apos;), ifthenelse(equals(getFromList(3, [input=drop_area_1]), &apos;B&apos;), 0, 1), 0), 0), 0) == 1</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </validationExpression>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Positions A, C, and D are correct, but your fourth position is wrong. Trees (B) must be last. By definition, trees are acyclic structures with exactly $n-1$ edges for $n$ vertices. They cannot contain any cycles, including Hamiltonian cycles.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: A $\to$ C $\to$ D $\to$ B&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
              <points>0</points>
              <terminal>true</terminal>
              <fieldsToBeMarked id="47"/>
            </FeedbackRule>
          </feedbackRules>
